              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The exception is a busy multi-location studio whose regulars rebook constantly and would genuinely keep an icon on their phone—there, a native app can earn its keep. For everyone else, a mobile-first booking website gives clients the "app" they're picturing without the download wall or the platform tax. MyTattoo.Software is built mobile-first for exactly this reason, so your booking page works like an app the moment a client taps your link.
        </p>

        <h2 id="pricing" class="text-3xl font-bold text-brand-navy mt-12 mb-6">Tattoo Booking App Pricing &amp; Affordable Options</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-6">
          Tattoo booking app pricing generally falls into two models: a flat monthly subscription, or a "free" tool that takes a percentage of every booking. Understanding the difference is the key to keeping costs down as you get busier—because the cheapest option on day one can quietly become the most expensive once your calendar fills up.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
          Across the wider market, typical cost ranges look roughly like this (these are general industry figures, not MyTattoo prices):
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li><strong>Solo-artist tools:</strong> commonly around £20–£40 per month for booking, deposits, and reminders on a single calendar.</li>
          <li><strong>Studio/multi-artist plans:</strong> typically £80–£150 per month as you add artists, calendars, and reporting.</li>
          <li><strong>Per-booking / commission models:</strong> often 3–5% of each booking. These advertise as "free" or low-cost but scale directly with your success—a busy artist taking £6,000 a month in bookings could pay £180–£300 monthly, far more than a flat plan.</li>
          <li><strong>Payment processing:</strong> separate from the software, card fees of roughly 2.9% + 30p per transaction are standard whichever platform you choose.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
          The cheapest way to start is almost always a flat-rate plan with predictable monthly costs: you get full functionality, your costs stay predictable, and you avoid handing over a slice of every deposit. Watch for per-booking fees disguised as low headline pricing, "free" tiers that can't actually take deposits (the one feature that prevents no-shows), and tools that charge extra for SMS reminders.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">
          MyTattoo.Software is open to independent tattoo artists, and right now there's no platform fee at all—no commission, no per-booking fee, and no monthly subscription while we're getting started. You connect your own Stripe account, so each deposit (you set the amount, £50 by default) goes straight to you and only Stripe's standard card-processing fee applies. You can find out more on our <a href="/pricing/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">pricing page</a>, and model the payback against your own no-show rate with the <a href="/tattoo-studio-calculator/" class="text-brand-red hover:underline">studio revenue calculator</a>.
        </p>

